mer Bottom in Selborne and Cranmore in Aldershot (both Hampshire), and East and West Cranmore (Somerset), all named from Old English <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ + <i>mere</i> ‘lake, pool’ or <i>mōr</i> ‘moor, marshy ground’. See also   Cranmore  , with which there may have been some confusion."],"variants":[{"name":"Cranmore","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Worcestershire): variant of   Cranmer  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Sutterton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Butterton (Staffs, Westm)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Edmund","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protector’. It was borne by several early royal and saintly figures, including a 9th-century king of East Anglia killed by invading Danes, allegedly for his adherence to Christianity. In the 16th and 17th centuries, there was a good deal of interchange between <i>Edmund</i> and <i>Edward</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Edmund Cranmer of Sutterton was born about 1400, in Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas de Cranmer, was 23 and his mother, Mrs Alice Cranmer, was 15. He had at least 1 son with Isabella Aslacton."},"et":{"Abt 1400–":"umbes 1400–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1425–Male":"1425–Surnud","1378–1450":"1378–1450","1386–1461":"1386–1461","1425":"1425","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","about 1425":"umbes 1425","1386":"1386","1461":"1461","1450":"1450","Abt 1400":"umbes 1400","1407":"1407","1405":"1405","Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Aslacton, Watton Parish, England":"Aslacton, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sutterton, , Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1400–":"noin 1400–Kuollut","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1425–Male":"1425–Kuollut","1378–1450":"1378–1450","1386–1461":"1386–1461","1425":"1425","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","about 1425":"noin 1425","1386":"1386","1461":"1461","1450":"1450","Abt 1400":"noin 1400","1407":"1407","1405":"1405","Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Aslacton, Watton Parish, England":"Aslacton, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sutterton, , Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1400–":"environ 1400–Décédé","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","1405–Female":"1405–Décédée","1425–Male":"1425–Décédé","1378–1450":"1378–1450","1386–1461":"1386–1461"